<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceReactor     09-10 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Reactor,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Proposed Funding Cut Could Leave Reactor's Future in
Doubt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department wants to curtail
development of a nuclear reactor to power weapons for a space-based
missile shield or for manned bases on the moon, according to a
published report.
   The New York Times in its Monday editions quoted federal
officials as saying that the department wants to stop spending on
the reactor because of rising budget pressure and opposition from
private groups and Congress.
   The Energy Department now provides most of the funding for the
4.2-ton reactor, known as the SP-100, which is meant to generate 100
kilowatts of electricity and to fit in the space shuttle, the
newspaper said.
   One Pentagon official told the Times the proposed cut would leave
the reactor program ``severely crippled.''
   But other officials who were not identified by the newspaper said
the proposed cut could be a ploy to get other federal agencies to
increase their financial support.
   This fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30, the Energy Department is
paying $56 million to support the reactor's development while the
space agency is paying $10 million and the Pentagon another $10
million.
   The SP-100 program began in 1983. A government audit last year
found the program seriously flawed and in danger of failing.
   On the moon, the reactor could be used to power a manned base
through the lunar night. In space, it could be used to power
anti-missile arms in orbit around the earth.
   It has drawn criticism from Congress for its potential military
uses.
   Rep. George E. Brown Jr., D-Calif., recently introduced
legislation calling for an international ban on putting reactors in
orbit and for limiting their use to deep space missions.
</TEXT>
