<FIRST>r p PM-Wright'sSeat     09-10 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright's Seat,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidates Sling Endorsements, Question Qualifications</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICE GRAVINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former House Speaker Jim Wright is
backing Pete Geren, but a TV doctor is counting on heavyweight
endorsements of his own to put a Republican congressman in the seat
Wright occupied 34 years.
   With little campaign time and few policy differences to
distinguish themselves, Democrat Geren and political newcomer Dr.
Bob Lanier are touting endorsements and their backgrounds to sway
voters in Tuesday's runoff election.
   Just getting the vote out is a challenge. Only a fifth of the
district's voters went to the polls in Aug. 12's special election to
fill Wright's unexpired term.
   Wright resigned June 30 after a House ethics investigation turned
up 69 instances of alleged rules violations.
   Still, he was greeted as a vanquished hero upon his return to
Fort Worth and remains popular in the district.
   Geren, 37, has started using radio spots by Wright and has
brought the former congressman with him on campaign appearances.
Geren, a former aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, also has that Texas
Democrat's endorsement.
   ``Jim Wright is proud of his years of service to this community,
but he recognizes that his seat is going to someone new, and he's
been very careful not to interject himself in any way that would
suggest that he's trying to control things,'' Geren said.
   Lanier, host of the nationally syndicated television show ``60
Second Housecall,'' is relieved Wright hasn't done more for Geren.
   ``We initially feared it quite a bit. We thought it would make a
major difference,'' said Lanier, a pediatric allergist. ``But it
hasn't been quite as much as we anticipated.''
   The 44-year-old Lanier has some of his own big guns: endorsements
from President Bush and former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry.
   The candidates have similar stands on major issues.
   Both oppose abortion but would not make it illegal, want better
health care funding for the elderly and support strong measures
against illegal drugs.
   Lanier has tried to make residency an issue, claiming Geren
doesn't live in the district. He accuses the lawyer, who comes from
a wealthy family, of being out of touch with voters.
   Geren counters that Lanier hasn't voted in recent elections and
lacks experience in public office.
   Lanier garnered 39 percent of the vote and Geren 32 percent in
the special election that trimmed the field from eight candidates.
   Lanier said he is ``swimming upstream'' as the Republican
candidate, but believes Fort Worth might be ready for change. Since
1980, voters here have helped elect Ronald Reagan, Bush and GOP Sen.
Phil Gramm. Texas is represented by nine Republicans and 20
Democrats in Congress.
   Democrats are hoping for a voter backlash against the Republicans
for what happened to Wright.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram recently endorsed Geren, as have
state educators, senior citizens and labor officials.
   The local police association has endorsed Lanier.
   The election is one of two being held Tuesday to choose
successors to congressmen who resigned amid ethics problems. In
California, voters will decide among eight candidates for the seat
of former Democratic House Whip Tony Coelho, who resigned in
mid-June as questions were raised about his financial dealings.
</TEXT>
