<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Scandinavian Airlines System plane
returning from Greece lost part of its tail while landing at
Stockholm's international airport, but no one was hurt, an SAS
spokesman said Sunday.
   The MD-82, a modernized DC-9, was arriving at Arlanda airport
from Athens with 156 passengers aboard when the incident occurred
Saturday night.
   Spokesman Knut Lovstuhagen said in an interview that the plane
lost its tail cone, which plays a minor role in the plane's
aerodynamics and which is released during emergency evacuations.
   The cause of the mishap was being investigated.
   Lovstuhagen said the passengers, mostly Swedish tourists,
probably did not even notice the loss of the cone, since it is
placed outside the pressurized cabin and does not affect
maneuverability.
