<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1359EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Reilly-CleanAir     09-10 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reilly-Clean Air,xxx</SECOND>
<HEAD>``No Other Way,'' Reilly Says of Cleaner Auto Fuel Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   EPA Administrator William Reilly on Sunday
defended the administration's plan to require cleaner-burning
alternatives to gasoline in the worst-polluted cities, saying
``there is no other way'' to curb smog.
   Appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Reilly also said
alternative fuels can compete economically with gasoline.
Alternative automotive fuels such as methanol, ethanol and natural
gas a linchpin of the Bush administration's clean air plan.
   The environment subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee will hold a hearing on the plan Tuesday.
   The petroleum industry contends the alternative-fuels proposal
would put its members at an unfair disadvantage against the makers
of the other fuels. Methanol, for instance, is derived from natural
gas or coal.
   The petroleum industry says cleaner-burning gasoline can be
developed and should be allowed.
   The automobile industry contends it may not be able to develop
the technology to meet the proposed 1995 deadline for supplying half
a million alternative-fuel cars to the nine dirtiest cities by 1995.
   Reilly said, however: ``The fact is the automobile remains about
half, a little less than half, of the problem even though we've made
great gains since the early 1970s in cleaning up pollution from
automobile tailpipes. ...
   ``We've got to go back in and do better, and the major
opportunity we have is alternative fuels.''
   Reilly also said ``it's not at all clear'' that alternative fuels
would cost more.
   The president's Council of Economic Advisors has been unable to
come up with a precise estimate of the cost differential for the
alternative fuels because of the distant deadlines, Reilly said.
   ``But we are reasonably confident that the range of cost is
likely to be close,'' he said. ``We don't see a significantly
increased expense for some of the alternative fuels.''
   Reilly said the administration is ``open to the kinds of fuels
that are used ... provided they get the pollution reductions that we
need, but for many cities in the country we see no other way to get
there than to change the fuel mix.''
   Discussing the proposal in general, Reilly said the chief issue
will be the $14 billion to $19 billion cost and who pays it.
   ``The whole question of imposing the kinds of expense that it's
going to take to clean up the air ... obviously is going to entail a
great debate: how those costs are borne; what segments of society;
in some cases with respect to acid rain, what regions?'' he said.
</TEXT>
