<FIRST>u p AM-DetroitMayor Bjt   09-10 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Mayor, Bjt,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleman Young Far Ahead in Detroit Primary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN L. ADLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   So confident is Coleman Young of breezing through
Tuesday's non-partisan mayoral primary that the normally combative
dean of U.S. black mayors is taking the high road or no road against
his 12 opponents.
   He won't fight them, and he rarely faces them.
   Thus the big question in the primary in the nation's
sixth-largest city is who will finish second and face Young in the
Nov. 7 runoff. At 71, Young seeks an unprecedented fifth four-year
term.
   Accountant Tom Barrow, 40, whom Young easily defeated in 1985, is
working hard to overtake John Conyers, 60, a 13-term congressman
whose name recognition alone may carry him into the runoff. Farther
back in the pack are City Council President Erma Henderson and
businessman Charles Costa.
   A poll released Aug. 27 by WJBK-TV found 38 percent of 413
respondents supported Young, 12 percent Conyers and 9 percent
Barrow. Henderson had 4.4 percent and Costa 1.5 percent, with 30
percent undecided. The margin of error was 4.8 points.
   Only Conyers is given much of a chance against Young in November.
   Young, despite taking a beating in the news media for most of his
current term, seems to have all the advantages. Among them:
   _A reported $5 million in campaign funds.
   _A 15-year incumbency and a record of accomplishment to go with
it. He kept a promise from his first campaign to bring affirmative
action to an overwhelmingly white police department, which now is 52
percent black and 20 percent female; he expanded City Airport and
Cobo Convention Center, and he has helped Detroit banks pledge more
than $2 billion in loans to city residents.
   _Support from the city's most influential unions, leaders of its
largest black churches, most of the city's state representatives,
and the Michigan Chronicle, the state's largest black newspaper.
Conyers and Barrow also are black, as are two-thirds of Detroit's 1
million people.
   Conyers' political service consists of a quarter-century in
Congress, and he has a national reputation, though his last-minute
candidacy just before a filing deadline didn't help much.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson has endorsed Conyers. So did The Detroit
Free Press, which had supported Young's four previous election bids
but denounced his ``lack of leadership'' the past four years. The
newspaper said Conyers ``would provide Detroit its best assurance of
a full debate and a real choice in November.''
   Barrow practically never stopped campaigning since he lost to
Young 61 percent to 39 percent in 1985. A nephew of boxer Joe Louis,
Barrow has no experience in office, and some observers feel he has
dues to pay in the rough-and-tumble world of Detroit politics before
he can expect to be mayor.
   Barrow's greatest accomplishment was leading last year's
opposition to Young's third effort to bring casino gambling to
Detroit. His door-to-door politicking also has given him more
visibility, and The Detroit News endorsed him as more conservative
than Young and Conyers.
   One matter that put Young into the headlines a few months ago _
the disclosure that he had fathered a child by a former city
administrator _ hasn't been much of a campaign issue.
   Young's greatest problem might be the perception that he's been
around too long. The need for a change has been the central theme of
Conyers' and Barrow's campaigns; they have accused the mayor of
neglecting neighborhoods at the expense of downtown development and
not doing enough about drug abuse among police officers, though
Young did get a judge to approve drug testing for patrolmen.
   ``There's something called the ABC vote _ Anybody But Coleman,''
said Wilbur Rich, an associate professor of political science at
Wayne State University who wrote a biography of Young.
   But that may not help Young's foe in the runoff, Rich said.
``Those people who have an ax to grind will show up for the primary,
but don't look for them in November.''
   Should Conyers finish second Tuesday, Rich looks for a bloody
campaign for the runoff, focusing on issues including drugs, crime
and neighborhood services.
   ``Conyers is not a guy Young can knock out easily. Conyers has a
lot of national visibility. But if it gets down to the cliche,
sound-bite kind of stuff, Young will be in his element,'' Rich said.
   Young's campaigning appears designed to keep him clear of
multicandidate events, where he might be forced or tempted to answer
one of his challengers. He says he's avoided such appearances to
give his challengers a chance to present their proposals.
   Young briefly encountered Conyers at a Labor Day parade. Young
walked a block of the parade route, then hopped in his limousine and
rode to the reviewing stand. That brought knocks from Conyers and
Barrow about Young's stamina.
   Instead, Young has campaigned as The Mayor. During the last week
in August, he announced a new $33 million soft drink bottling plant
that will employ 300, an $86 million bond sale and the construction
of 500 housing units with $30 million in state money.
   In November, Rich said, ``The winner can't be just as good as
Coleman; they'll have to prove they are better than Coleman.''
</TEXT>
