<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--CocaineSeizure     09-10 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cocaine Seizure,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colorado Cops Seize 1,100 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the state's largest cocaine seizure ever, state
police seized 1,100 pounds of cocaine being shipped in a
semi-trailer truck, according to a report published Sunday.
   U.S. Attorney Mike Norton in Denver confirmed on Saturday that
cocaine had been seized and at least two people had been arrested,
but wouldn't give details of the incident. State police said only
that a large quantity of drugs had been seized and details would be
divulged at a news conference Monday.
   The Denver Post, quoting law enforcement sources who would not
give their names, said state police seized 1,100 pounds of cocaine
Friday afternoon from a semi-trailer truck headed eastbound on
Interstate 70 near Grand Junction. Two men aboard the truck, age 19
and 20, were arrested, the Post said.
   Colorado's record cocaine seizure had been 738 pounds confiscated
at the Jefferson County Airport in May 1988 in a Drug Enforcement
Administration sting.
