<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1535EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MinorityLending     09-10 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minority Lending,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boston Mayor to Keep City's Money in Banks Lending to Minorities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city will begin steering its money to banks
committed to serving minority neighborhoods' credit needs, Mayor
Raymond Flynn has announced.
   The move comes less than two weeks after a federal report said
white Boston neighborhoods have gotten more mortgage loans than
black neighborhoods.
   Flynn said Saturday he will sign an executive order establishing
a ``linked deposit'' program requiring the city treasurer to
evaluate banks on such factors as home mortgages, small-business
loans and other services.
   ``We don't see this as a panacea,'' Treasurer Lee Jackson said.
``But on the other hand, we think it's important we put our money
where our mouth is and do what we can to encourage positive
investment behavior.''
   The mayor also said he will establish a Community Banking
Commission to monitor lending practices of Boston banks and
recommend ways to improve services to city neighborhoods.
   Boston city deposits range from $50 million to $350 million at
any given time and are split among 20 banks and money-market funds.
Banks bid for deposits.
   In its recent report, the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston said
that between 1982 and 1987, the largely white areas of Boston
received 24 percent more mortgage loans than black neighborhoods.
The study urged bankers to reach out to minority consumers.
   A Boston community group issued a similar study a month ago.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. House Banking Committee said Friday it will
hold a hearing Sept. 29 in Boston in response to the Federal Reserve
study.
   Also on Friday, the Massachusetts Bankers Association offered a
series of proposals to ease inequities in money services between
black and white neighborhoods statewide.
   The proposals include setting up a Minority Business Investment
Center to encourage expansion of minority-owned companies, and
changing mortgage lending practices to increase minority access to
financial institutions.
</TEXT>
