<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-10 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Bayh has signed another veto _
nixing his own official autograph.
   With the stroke of a pen, the governor has written off as a loss
the signature affixed to thousands of documents during the first
eight months of his administration.
   In its place, Bayh has penned a new signature that shuns modern
efficiency in favor of old-time legibility.
   ``I started seeing these documents coming back to me with my
signature on them and I looked at them and thought to myself, `Boy,
that's not a very good example of penmanship,''' Bayh said Friday.
   ``So I took the initiative myself and insisted I'm going to take
my time and write a nice, legible signature rather than this scrawl
I hurriedly put down before,'' he said.
   The governor acknowledged his autograph had consisted of ``an `E'
and an elongated squiggle'' followed by a ``B'' and two loops, one
descending and one ascending.
   The new autograph with the full eight letters, each more or less
readable, has replaced the old one on the machine used to affix
Bayh's signature to thousands of documents he doesn't have time to
sign himself.
   Bayh said a penmanship teacher had written to him suggesting he
take more care in signing his name. And he admitted feeling a little
sheepish about the reaction from some people he gave autographs,
like a high school graduate at a commencement Bayh spoke at this
spring.
   ``This one young guy was the first up to me, and I proceeded to
give him my quick signature,'' said Bayh. ``He looked at it and
said, `Come on, what's that?'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WALTON BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After shooting 1,013 weddings,
photographer Bob Shanklin got married himself and found love at
first lighthouse.
   While honeymooning in New England two years ago, Shanklin, now
64, and his new bride, Sandra, 50, took their first pictures of
lighthouses. Now they are about a quarter of the way toward their
goal of photographing every one of an estimated 850 lighthouses
nationwide, many of them in various states of disrepair.
   ``I think it's kind of the romance of the sea,'' Mrs. Shanklin
said.
   ``I think it's a symbol of security,'' her husband said.
   Shanklin gave up a measure of security in putting aside a studio
and then a commercial photography business to sell photos as art.
   ``For years, I shot what everyone wanted me to shoot, and I got
to the point where I couldn't stand to take pictures of people any
more,'' Shanklin said. ``I almost pulled out of (photography) and
then decided I'd start shooting what my heart told me to shoot.''
   Shanklin met his wife, a seascape artist, at an art show. They
now make a living selling their photographs at shows and to
publications. Although they photograph other subjects, the
lighthouses have sold best, particularly in this year of the 200th
anniversary of the U.S. Lighthouse Service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOREHEAD CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toupees and transplants were heartily
booed at the 16th annual convention of the Bald Headed Men of
America.
   ``It's not what's on the head that's important; it's what's in
the head,'' said John Capps, the organization's founder.
   More than 30 of the organization's 30,000 members attended the
event in this aptly named town, engaging in a marathon of bald humor
and participating in competitions including Most Kissable Bald Head,
Smoothest, Sexiest, Best All-Round and Solar Dome.
   ``You really don't need those lights,'' one baldie joked to TV
news crews videotaping the assemblage of shining pates.
   Steve Austin of New York City feared not winning the competition
for Smallest Bald Spot.
   ``I think I'm going to lose by a hair,'' he said.
</TEXT>
