<FIRST>r w AM-AncientForests     09-10 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ancient Forests,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Over Old-Growth Logging Could Come This Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The showdown over logging of the ancient
forests of the Northwest could come as early as this week when House
and Senate negotiators consider legislation imposing an uneasy truce
in the bitter battle between environmentalists and the timber
industry.
   Both sides have mounted intense lobbying campaigns aimed at the
20 or so lawmakers who will consider the interior appropriations
bill for the coming fiscal year.
   Attached to the Senate-passed version of the spending bill is an
amendment offered by Sens. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., and Brock Adams,
D-Wash., that has outraged environmentalists and has the reluctant
support of the industry.
   National environmental groups have made defeat of the amendment
one of their top legislative priorities this year and
conservationists from around the country have been prowling the
halls of Congress over the past week buttonholing members and their
top aides.
   Two loaded logging trucks from the Northwest will roll onto
Capitol Hill on Monday for an industry-sponsored rally. More than
150 people, including loggers and millworkers from 22 Oregon and
Washington communities, will spearhead the industry lobbying drive
this week.
   At stake is the future of the cathedral-like forests on federal
lands in Washington state, Oregon and northern California. The
stands of old-growth trees, some up to 1,000 years old, provide
prime habitat for the northern spotted owl and timber for mills that
serve as the sole source of income for residents of dozens of small
communities.
   ``The Hatfield-Adams rider will kill spotted owls as sure as a
drunken logger with a shotgun,'' said Andy Kerr, conservation
director of the Oregon Natural Resources Council.
   Mark Rey, executive director of the newly-formed American Forest
Resource Alliance, said the fate of small, independent timber
operations was on the line and if environmentalists have their way
the forests will be closed to logging creating an economic
catastrophe for the one-mill towns.
   ``We are on record supporting the legislation reluctantly and we
hope it passes,'' said Rey, adding the that the amendment provided
only a short-term fix and that the battle will continue as the Fish
and Wildlife Service decides whether to list the owl as a threatened
species.
   Environmentalists are especially incensed over provisions in the
amendment they say would limit their access to the federal courts
where they have won a string of legal victories, including
injunctions that at one point tied up almost half the timber sales
planned in the federal forests this year.
   The legislation would bar federal courts from enjoining or
overturning any timber sales planned in the federal forests of the
Northwest over the next 11 months known to contain spotted owls.
   In addition, the legislation would require that environmentalists
release more than half of the timber currently enjoined from sale.
   If the environmentalists do not agree to release the timber, the
Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management would be allowed to
proceed with the sales despite the injunctions.
   The legislation would also allow for the sale of 10 billion board
feet of timber through the end of fiscal 1990 and the protection of
blocks of ``significant'' stands of old growth through a policy
known as ``minimum fragmentation.''
   The entire Northwest congressional delegation supports the
legislation, but there is formidable opposition elsewhere.
</TEXT>
