<FIRST>r w AM-BraveryMedals     09-10 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bravery Medals,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Awards Going to Hawaiian Girl; California Youth</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release at 5 p.m. EDT - time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A girl who saved a tourist from drowning in
Hawaii and a California youth who disarmed a fellow student holding
70 people hostage will receive the 1988 Young American Medals for
Bravery, the Justice Department said Sunday.
   Angela Marie Campanoli, now 12, dove into rough waters near her
home in Maui last Oct. 5 to save a Japanese woman who was being
swept out to sea. She held the woman's head above water until help
arrived, the department said.
   Ruben Ortega, 19, of Alhambra, Calif., disarmed a student who
brought an assault rifle into an English class at San Gabriel High
School on April 26, 1988 and held 70 students hostage for a half
hour.
   Ruben, who was one of the hostages, risked his life by grabbing
the rifle and the gunman, wrestling him to the ground.
   The youth and other students held the gunmen to the ground until
police arrived.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said that the two youths would
be given the awards by President Bush at a date to be announced
later by the White House.
   Thornburgh said an 18-year-old Boston high school senior who
warned fellow students of the dangers of drugs and AIDS and a
17-year-old New Jersey youth who worked with disabled Boy Scouts
will be given the 1988 Young American Medals for Service.
   Freddy Torres, 18, of Boston, will be cited for his work urging
young people to avoid drugs warning them of the dangers of AIDS.
   John Philip Donovan, 18, of River Vale, N.J., was junior
assistant scout master for a Boy Scout troop with learning and
physically disabled scouts. He also was the only youth member of a
local civic-pride organization and raised $6,500 for a Muscular
Dystrophy fund-raiser.
   The recipients of the awards, who are chosen for acts of bravery
or service during the previous year, were selected by FBI Director
William Sessions, Drug Enforcement Administration head John C. Lawn,
Stanley E. Morris, director of the U.S. Marshals Service and David
Runkel, Thornburgh's press secretary.
   The awards were begun in 1950 under an act of Congress that
requires the president to personally present them to the recipients.
</TEXT>
