<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Ukraine     09-10 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ukraine,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poet Named To Head Ukrainian Grass-roots Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ukrainian poet and political activist Ivan Drach
was elected Sunday to lead a new grass-roots group fighting for
greater sovereignty for the Soviet republic, a spokesman for a human
rights group said.
   Anatoly Dotsenko, a spokesman in Moscow for the Ukrainian
Helsinki Group that monitors human rights, said Sergei I. Konev, a
parliament member, was chosen as a deputy to Drach.
   The group, initially called the Ukrainian Popular Movement for
Perestroika, was renamed ``Rukh,'' Ukrainian for movement, on the
final day of a three-day meeting held in the republic's capital,
Kiev.
   Drach, a well-known activist in the Ukraine, failed to win a seat
in the the Congress of People's Deputies in spring elections.
   On Saturday, Konev and another speaker at the meeting called for
the removal of conservative Politburo member and Ukrainian Communist
Party chief Vladimir Shcherbitsky.
   Konev called on the grass-roots group ``to express its lack of
confidence in the government of the Ukraine headed by
Shcherbitsky,'' Dotsenko said.
   Shcherbitsky, 71, is the oldest of 12 men on the policy-making
Politburo and is considered one of the most conservative.
   Some Ukrainians blame him for covering up the radiation damage
from the Chernobyl nuclear power plant accident, for restraining the
local press and for arrests and harrassment of dissidents.
Thirty-one people died and hundreds were hospitalized in the
Chernobyl accident on April 26, 1986.
   Other speakers Saturday called for creation of a sovereign, free
Ukraine with a multiparty system.
   State television showed the meeting hall decorated with the
blue-and-yellow flags of the independent Ukraine. A Ukrainian
People's Republic was declared following the 1917 Russian
Revolution, but was overthrown the next year.
</TEXT>
