<FIRST>u i AM-MotherTeresa 2ndLd-Writethru a0704 09-10 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0704,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Improves After Receiving Pacemaker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th pvs, `Mother Teresa...' to CORRECT spelling of Dr.
Bilotta; picks up 9th pvs, `Press Trust...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mother Teresa's condition improved Sunday
after the Nobel laureate received a pacemaker to steady her
heartbeat and heavy doses of antibiotics to fight a fever, doctors
said.
   A statement issued by Woodlands Nursing Home said the 79-year-old
Roman Catholic nun known for her work with the poor was ``bright and
cheerful, had eaten with a good appetite and had a comfortable sleep
(Sunday) afternoon.''
   K.P. Mukherjee, the secretary of Woodlands Nursing Home, said
Mother Teresa still is in intensive care but ``responded well to the
treatment'' after a temporary pacemaker was fitted late Saturday.
   ``Her condition has improved further and she does not have
pneumonia,'' Mukherjee said. Earlier Sunday, a hospital source said
doctors feared Mother Teresa might be developing pneumonia.
   The hospital statement said Mother Teresa's blood platelet count
dropped Saturday, causing some anxiety among doctors, but was normal
by Sunday evening. Platelets are disc-shaped constituents of blood
that help it to clot.
   Pope John Paul II gave Mother Teresa a special blessing and sent
her a telegram with ``assurances of his prayers and spiritual
participation'' in her suffering, the Vatican said Sunday.
   Mother Teresa's longtime cardiologist in Rome, Dr. Vincenzo
Bilotta, is expected to arrive in Calcutta Monday, said Sister
Shanti of the Missionaries of Charity.
   Mother Teresa has suffered similar ailments in the past, due in
part to her refusal to rest, Bilotta said.
   Press Trust of India reported that Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
also plans to visit Mother Teresa on Monday.
   Her order of 3,000 nuns, devoted to the destitute and dying, on
Sunday observed what they call ``Inspiration Day,'' the anniversary
of the day in 1948 that Mother Teresa was inspired to set up her
Missionaries of Charity, Sister Shanti said. The order, recognized
by the Vatican in 1965, now has nuns working in 87 countries.
   Mother Teresa, who won the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize for her good
works, became ill Sept. 3.
   She was admitted to the hospital's intensive care unit last
Tuesday with a high fever and irregular heartbeat. She suffered a
heart attack Friday.
   Born in Yugoslavia, Mother Teresa received several honors for her
work with the poor in the eastern Indian city of Calcutta, including
the Presidential Medal of Freedom, the highest U.S. civilian award,
from President Reagan in 1985.
   Mother Teresa gave up a comfortable life as a convent teacher to
live and work among Calcutta's poor.
   Despite heart problems and failing eyesight in recent years, she
traveled widely and vigorously spoke out against abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
