<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-10 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Taste of Winter in the Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold air pushed across the Rockies onto the Plains on Sunday,
keeping daytime temperatures as low as the 30s and spreading snow
and rain, and thunderstorms were scattered across parts of the East.
   The unseasonably cool weather was caused by a large high pressure
area centered over central Alberta.
   Billings, Mont., had a record low of 33, and both Boise, Idaho,
and Yakima, Wash., tied their records of 36.
   Early afternoon temperatures were only in the 30s and 40s Sunday
over the northern Rockies and northern high Plains.
   The cold air along with an upper air disturbance over southern
Saskatchewan produced low clouds and light rain across the northern
Plains and Nebraska.
   Snow fell across sections of Montana, with 3 inches overnight at
Fairfield and an inch at Lewiston.
   From 3 to 6 inches of snow was expected to accumulate during the
night over the Big Horn Mountains west of Sheridan, Wyo.
   By contrast, hot, humid weather covered much of the Atlantic
Coast states and the Southeast with temperatures in the 90s into New
England. Burlington, Vt., tied its record at 90 degrees.
   Thunderstorms with locally heavy rain were scattered over central
and southeast Texas. Mexia got 3.91 inches of rain Sunday morning.
   Thunderstorms also were scattered ahead of a cold front from the
lower Mississippi Valley across the Tennessee Valley and the central
Appalachians to western New York state. Leland, Miss., received 3.31
inches of rain during the morning.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Cody, Wyo., to 100 at Palm Springs, Calif. Sunday's low
in the Lower 48 states was 23 at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from northern New England across the middle Atlantic Coast and much
of the Appalachians into the Tennessee Valley. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms also were forecast from the lower and middle
Mississippi Valley to the central Plains and Oklahoma into Colorado.
Showers were forecast from the upper Mississippi Valley across the
northern Plains into Wyoming. Snow was forecast over the mountains
of Wyoming and the Black Hills of South Dakota. Scattered
thunderstorms were forecast over Florida.
   Highs in the 40s were predicted over northern Wyoming and western
South Dakota; in the 50s and 60s from Idaho across the central
Rockies, much of the northern and central Plains and the upper
Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes; in the 90s from the
southern Atlantic Coast and Florida across the Gulf Coast region
into southern and eastern Texas, as well as over interior valleys of
California; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest; and in
the 70s and 80s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
