<DOCNO> AP890910-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1832EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-10 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Cabinet Nominees Questioned on Economic Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Finance Ministry nominee said Sunday
the economy can improve despite soaring inflation and a demoralized
workers. He spoke after lawmakers grilled candidates for the Soviet
bloc's first Cabinet not led by communists.
   A parliamentary committee confirmed economist Leszek Balcerowicz
in the combined post of deputy prime minister and finance minister,
after he outlined a plan to revise tax, wage and trade policies.
   Asked later on national television whether Poles could expect to
live better under the new Solidarity-led government, Balcerowicz
replied, ``There is a real chance.''
   He said, however,``Our economic point of departure is extremely
difficult. Therefore, I feel that no responsible person should be
going around making easy promises.''
   The Labor Ministry nominee, Jacek Kuron, also was approved in a
daylong session of the welfare committee, but Andrzej Kosiniak, the
Peasant Party candidate for the Health Ministry, was rejected.
   Two other nominees for farm policy and rural affairs ministries
failed to win approval during a first day of hearings on Friday.
   But the committee's opinion is not binding. The Sejm, the
powerful lower house of parliament, makes the final decision.
   Hearings on nominees for the Foreign Trade Ministry and chairman
of the national bank were scheduled for Monday, television news said.
   The Cabinet proposed by Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the
East bloc's first non-communist leader in more than four decades,
gives half of the 24 council seats to Solidarity.
   The communists have just four, although the party keeps the
strategic ministries of defense and the interior.
   The remaining seats are distributed among the Peasants and the
Democratic Party, which helped put Mazowiecki _ a top aide to
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa _ in office by breaking their
traditional alliance with the Communists.
   Parliament is to vote on the new government Tuesday, when
Mazowiecki is expected to outline his government's program.
   The Solidarity government faces triple-digit inflation, a $39
billion debt, and workers demoralized by long lines and poor quality
goods.
   The economic program outlined by Balcerowicz calls for
restructuring the tax system, implementing wage controls,
liberalizing foreign trade rules, and unifying the exchange rates.
   Balcerowicz told the parliamentary committee he left the
Communist Party after the military crackdown on the Solidarity trade
union in December 1981. He said he now belongs to the Warsaw chapter
of the Solidarity Citizens Committee.
   Solidarity was legalized after an April agreement with the
government, and won a sweeping victory in June parliamentary
elections, taking 161 seats in the 460-seat Sejm and 99 seats in the
new 100-seat Senate.
   Kuron, a veteran opposition activist, told the committee wages
should be set by the market, but that a minimum wage should be set
to protect workers. He said, however, the first task of the new
government was to stop inflation, which is thought to have reached
40 percent in August alone.
   He said the transition to a market economy and measures to
control inflation could lead to a drop in purchasing power, but that
the government would not abandon the disadvantaged.
   Economic journalist Aleksander Paszynski, the Solidarity
candidate for the building ministry, was approved by the local
government committee.
</TEXT>
