<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 2053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CivilRightsSlayings     09-10 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights Slayings,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Spied on Civil Rights Worker Before His Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three civil rights workers killed in
1964 was spied on three months before his death by a state
commission formed to maintain segregation, a newspaper reported
Sunday.
   The Mississippi Sovereignty Commission in March 1964 received a
report on the activities of Michael Schwerner and his wife, Rita, in
Meridian, said The Clarion-Ledger, which obtained commission
documents.
   The commission circulated a description and the license number of
a vehicle used by the Schwerners and other Congress of Racial
Equality workers, the newspaper said.
   Schwerner, Andrew Goodman and James Chaney were killed June 21,
1964, near Philadelphia, Miss. Their deaths and the subsquent
federal investigation were the basis for the film ``Mississippi
Burning.''
   The three, who were reported missing, were found buried in an
earthen dam on Aug. 4, 1964.
   The state never prosecuted the case, but a federal court
convicted seven Ku Klux Klan members of conspiring to deprive the
three of their civil rights. Another Klan member pleaded guilty,
eight were acquitted and the cases against three ended in a
mistrial. Most of the 19 men prosecuted are alive.
   State Attorney General Mike Moore has asked the FBI to help him
research the case to determine whether to bring state charges now.
   Schwerner's widow, Seattle attorney Rita Schwerner Bender, said
she was unaware of the surveillance. ``I didn't know they were
spying on me,'' she said.
   ``There was clearly a governmental investigation in an effort to
discredit the civil rights workers and participation in the
movement,'' Bender said. ``Now it would appear that there was
organized Mississippi state governmental misconduct.''
   The surveillance may have encouraged the slayings, University of
Mississippi history professor David Sansing said in Oxford.
   ``Those murders could have been prevented,'' Sansing said.
``Instead of being prevented, the power structure was in a way
encouraging them by this surveillance.
   ``They may not have said, `Go kill them,' but they sure made it
easy,'' he said.
   Former commission Director Erle Johnston of Forest said the
agency spied on the Schwerners but denied it had any connection with
the slayings.
   ``We had no knowledge of what happened,'' Johnston said. ``We
didn't have any involvement.
   ``The role of the commission in the murders was just making
reports,'' he said. ``We had no part in the arrests or prosecution.
We put down what we saw.''
   The commission was created by the 1956 Legislature to help
preserve segregation. It went out of business in 1973 after Gov.
Bill Waller vetoed funding.
   The main body of the commission's records remains sealed in a
state Department of Archives and History vault in Jackson on orders
of the 1977 Legislature. U.S. District Judge William H. Barbour Jr.
ruled July 27 that those records should be made public, but they
remain sealed pending appeals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
