<FIRST>r a AM-LotteryLawsuit     09-10 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lottery Lawsuit,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Sues Sexual Attacker For $5.86 Million in Lottery Winnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENTURA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman is suing the man convicted of
sexually attacking her, demanding the $5.86 million he won last year
in the California Lottery.
   Raymond Wilson, 20, a fast-food worker from Los Angeles, has
admitted he attacked Becky Rasnick, 28, while she jogged near her
home on Jan. 21. Police arrested him at his Santa Monica apartment
on Feb. 10.
   Wilson pleaded guilty to attempted rape on June 12, but insists
he never meant to rape or harm Mrs. Rasnick. On Aug. 10, Ventura
Superior Court Judge Charles McGrath sentenced him to five years'
probation, although the prosecutor had asked for up to six years in
prison.
   McGrath ordered Wilson to get therapy as a condition of
probation, to register with the state as a sex offender and to serve
one year in jail.
   Mrs. Rasnick and her husband, Ben, were outraged by the short
sentence, especially after Wilson used the proceeds from the lottery
he won last Oct. 12 to hire an expensive defense attorney and
psychologist.
   The Rasnicks are seeking $234,400 a year from Wilson's winnings.
They say they would use most of the money to fight abortion and
pornography.
   A smaller amount would be used to pay for Mrs. Rasnick's
continuing therapy, and reimburse her lost earnings as a church
teacher, the couple said.
   A victory for the Rasnicks would devastate Wilson, said his
lawyer, James Farley of Ventura.
   It ``could totally wipe out everything Ray has, leaving him
broke'' and unable to pay for the therapy he needs, he said.
   According to court records, Wilson was sexually abused by a male
baby sitter when he was 4 or 5 years old and has been obsessed with
sex since.
   ``I feel sorry for them both,'' Farley said of Rasnick and
Wilson. ``They both have their burdens to tote around.''
</TEXT>
