<HEAD>Iranian Deported After Serving Jail Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain on Sunday deported an Iranian who spent
nine years in a British prison for participating in a bombing
attempt, the government said.
   Kourosh Fouladi, a former doorman at the Iranian Embassy in
London, was arrested in 1980 after a bungled car bombing attempt. He
was convicted in 1982 and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   On Sunday, he was taken to Heathrow Airport and put on a flight
to Tehran, the Home Office said.
   In Tehran, officials said Britain's release of Fouladi was linked
to the plight of British businessman Roger Cooper, who was accused
of spying in Iran, where he has been imprisoned without trial since
1985.
   But a Foreign Office spokesman said, ``In no way is this linked.
He is simply being released because, with remission, he has served
his time.
   ``If the Iranians plan to let Roger Cooper go that would be
extremely welcome, but there is no indication that they have such
plans.''
   In response to a previous Iranian statement linking the two
cases, Foreign Office minister William Waldegrave said in April
there was no provision in British law for exchanging Fouladi for
Cooper.
