<FIRST>r a AM-BoiseViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0707 09-10 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boise Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0707,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calm Returns to City After Union Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with six grafs to RECAST. Picks up 7th graf, `The violence.''.
SUBS last graf with four grafs to UPDATE with state briefing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police escorted non-union
construction workers back to work at a paper mill Sunday as
residents prayed for an end to the turmoil that erupted into a
violent labor protest.
   Pro-union protesters Saturday stormed a housing camp for
non-union workers at the Boise Cascade paper mill in this town of
6,500 residents on the Canadian border, setting trailers on fire and
overturning vehicles.
   About 45 law enforcement officers used tear gas to disperse the
crowd estimated at 400. Five people were injured, and 32 people were
arrested, authorities said. Boise spokesman Andrew Drysdale
estimated damage at $1.3 million.
   ``Yesterday was a sad day for us in International Falls,'' the
Rev. Robert A. Kitchen told his congregation at the Faith United
Church of Christ. ``It was a day of desperation, of anger, of
hopelessness, perhaps.''
   Kitchen, describing the labor unrest as ``an open wound that we
know has ripped our community apart,'' prayed that the community
pull together and denounce the violence.
   About 370 non-union workers riding buses escorted by police
returned to the plant Sunday morning to work on a $535 million
expansion project, Drysdale said. Crews had been told not to report
to work Saturday following the protest.
   The violence stemmed from Boise Cascade's decision to hire
non-union general contractor BE&amp;K of Birmingham, Ala., to expand its
International Falls mill, a move that sparked a wildcat strike by
union members in July.
   Union officials have not sanctioned the strike and say they have
tried to dissuade protesters from violence or mass demonstrations.
   ``We had planned a rally here on the state Capitol steps next
Saturday, and urged them to come to that rally,'' Bill Peterson,
head of the Minnesota Building Trades Council, said in St. Paul.
   ``My attempts were to stop any other rally. We think any rally at
International Falls ought not be held because we were sure that,
tensions running as high as they were, there could be some
problems,'' Peterson said.
   Drysdale said union workers should not blame BE&amp;K and its
subcontractors for being out of work.
   ``Eighteen of the first 20 contracts on this project went to
union contractors,'' Drysdale said Sunday. ``But they wanted it all.
We gave them a tremendous amount of work on this project.
   ``This is not a case of us excluding the unions. We tried to
include them.''
   Iron Range Building Trades Council President Brad Skarich of
Virginia, Minn., could not be reached for comment on Drysdale's
statements. He did not immediately return messages left on an
answering machine.
   The 32 people arrested were being held at the Koochiching County
Jail pending court appearances this week on charges of criminal
damage to property and contempt of court.
   Law enforcement officers remained on alert Saturday night in case
of renewed violence but none was reported, said Sheriff William
Elliott.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich, acting on a request by local law enforcement
officials, put National Guardsmen on alert, but did not send them
into the city. Perpich took the guard off alert status Sunday
afternoon.
   Elliott and Boise Cascade officials had been critical of the
decision not to send National Guardsmen to International Falls.
Because of its remote location, Elliott said it could be difficult
to get adequate help from other law enforcement agencies.
   Perpich and state law enforcement officials Sunday said there
reports of possible trouble, but Perpich said the state could not
send in the Guard simply in anticipation of trouble. He said there
was no reason to send the troops after the violence had ended.
   The governor said evidence including videotapes made by state
Bureau of Criminal Apprehension agents would be sent to the U.S.
attorney's office for possible federal charges.
</TEXT>
