<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Plane     09-10 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Plane,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll in Amazon Plane Crash Rises to Twelve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll in last week's crash
landing of a jetliner in the Amazon jungle increased to 12 Sunday,
when a 2-year-old boy died from injuries sustained in the accident,
a hospital spokesman said.
   Bruno Metazo had been in a coma since he arrived at the hospital
on Thursday, according to Luis Candido of the Albert Einstein
Hospital in Sao Paulo, 270 miles southwest of Rio.
   On Sept. 3, the Varig airlines jet with 54 people on board made
an emergency landing in the Amazon rain forest. Nine passengers died
when the plane crashed through the jungle and two died aboard air
force evacution planes.
   Two passengers remained in critical condition Sunday, including
3-year-old Bruna Lorena Coimbra Costa, doctors said.
   The Boeing 737-200 vanished while on the last leg of a regularly
scheduled flight between Sao Paulo and Belem, 2,000 miles northwest
of Rio at the mouth of the Amazon river.
   Air force planes located the jetliner Tuesday after four
survivors walked to a remote ranch and radioed for help.
