<HEAD>Former President Nails Anti-Drug Campaign for Alcoholism Omission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ford criticized the Bush
administration for omitting alcohol abuse from its anti-drug
campaign and attacked the Reagan years for continuing the nation's
serious economic woes.
   ``I basically endorse President Bush's drug strategy,'' Ford said
Saturday while speaking to the 19th annual Vail Symposium.
   However, the former president called alcohol abuse more damaging
to society than cocaine and other drugs.
   Ford said four times more people were killed in 1987 in
alcohol-related traffic accidents than accidents involving drugs. He
said alcohol abuse had cost society $120 billion, compared with $60
billion from drug abuse.
   The Bush administration's campaign against drugs focuses on
anti-drug education for youth, but ``the drug problem is an equally
serious challenge'' among adults, Ford said.
   Former first lady Betty Ford several years ago underwent
treatment for alcoholism and addiction to prescription drugs.
   Ford, who owns a home in Vail, also lambasted the Reagan
administration and Congress for failing to adequately reduce the
federal budget.
   ``Over the last seven or eight years, both the White House and
Congress have done a very inadequate job of managing the budget,''
Ford said.
   He called ``inexcusable'' the annual $180 billion budget deficit
during the Reagan administration years. And he termed
``unacceptable'' the current projected deficit of $110 billion to
$150 billion.
