<FIRST>r w AM-GenericDrugs 1stld-writethru a0697 09-10 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic Drugs, 1st ld-writethru, a0697, 580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Generic Drug Companies on Campaign to Rebuild Confidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf to CORRECT spelling of Dyazide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scandal swirling around some generic drug
companies is forcing the industry to regroup and is refueling a
long-running rivalry between makers who emphasize brandname
medicines and their competitors who sell only lower-priced clones.
   Disclosures of fraud and corruption within the industry and at
the Food and Drug Administration, and admissions that brandname
products were substituted for generic drugs in sampling tests, have
shaken confidence within the industry.
   ``We have to rebuild confidence'' in generic drugs, said Jay
Molishever, a spokesman for the Generic Pharmaceutical Industry
Association, a trade group representing generic drug makers.
   Generics are used to fill about a third of all prescriptions.
   The largest of the generic drug makers under scrutiny, Bolar
Pharmaceuticals of Copiague, N.Y., has begun a public relations
drive in the wake of the FDA's move to take the company's generic
version of the widely prescribed, high-blood-pressure drug Dyazide
off the market.
   The company has hired a public relations firm and is sending
letters to physicians, pharmacists and customers trying to bolster
confidence in its product, said a company official who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   The FDA has said that while it does not consider Bolar's drug to
be unsafe, it questions whether the drug was manufactured under
specifications approved by the agency.
   In a mailing to physicians earlier this month, Bolar said the
generic drug industry ``has become the victim of irresponsible and
unsubstantiated charges.''
   Bolar employees also stepped into the fray, taking out a
full-page advertisement in The New York Times and another in Newsday
earlier this month to defend the company's management as
``reputable, honest and caring.''
   The employees also said they were ``outraged'' at U.S. Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of a House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee that has been investigating the generic drug industry,
``for creating a climate of fear and distrust'' within the industry
``because of the fraudulent deeds of a few.''
   Analysts said last week it was too early to tell whether Bolar's
sales have been affected by the FDA's action against its
largest-selling drug. Analysts say Bolar's generic Dyazide accounts
for more than half of the company's earnings.
   Bolar's drug is the only generic version left on the market since
Vitarine Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Springfield Gardens, N.Y., withdrew
its generic Dyzaide from the market after admitting it had
substituted the brandname drug for its own in tests to win FDA
approval.
   Kaiser Permanente, the Oakland, Calif.-based health-maintenance
organization, has pulled Bolar's drug from its pharmacy shelves.
   However, the major drugstore chains, including the American
Association of Retired Persons pharmacies, are continuing to supply
the product, said Hemant K. Shah, a Warren, N.J., analyst who
follows the generic drug industry.
   Brandname companies have long questioned whether generic drugs
work as well as the name-brand products. But as generics gained
public acceptance and began taking a greater share of the business
from the brandname market, many of these companies have gotten into
the generic business themselves, often making generic versions of
their own products after the patents expire.
   Meanwhile, SmithKline Beecham, which makes Dyazide, is doing its
own public relations with a letter to physicians and pharmacists
informing them of the developments in the generic drug investigation
and reminding them that their brandname product was not affected.
   The investigation ``certainly reaffirms the necessity for
dispensing your Dyazide prescriptions with the branded product,''
the letter said.
   ``This was to clarify confusion,'' said Jeremy Heymsfeld, a
spokesman for SmithKline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
