<SECOND>AM-50th Anniversaries,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>773 Couples Celebrate 50 Years of Marriage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After living through romance and reality, falling
in love and then making it work, 773 couples gathered Sunday to
celebrate 50 years of wedded bliss at Holy Name Roman Catholic
Cathedral.
   The theme was the more the merrier, as about 2,000 children,
grandchildren and great-grandchildren packed into the nearby
Cathedral School auditorium to watch the Mass celebrated by Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin via closed-circuit television.
   ``Sometimes you feel like it isn't worth it, sure,'' said Samuel
Smith, of the city's South Side who will be married for 50 years in
November. ``But you say you're together for better or worse and deal
with it.''
   Marsha Ross, a volunteer for Marriage Encounters for Family
Ministries, said the ceremony had special significance for the
couples.
   ``For the cardinal to be the main celebrant is an extremely
powerful moment for most of these couples,'' she said.
   But the main focus of the Mass, celebrated for the past 12 years,
was to balance some of the negative press about marriage and
divorce, Ms. Ross added.
   ``This balances that with a real vision of the commitment that
you see 773 times 50 years represents,'' Ms. Ross said. ``I mean its
a very powerful witness to ... well, marriage.''
   Catherine and Joseph Bergthold, from the city's South Side, were
married Sept. 9, 1949, and now have 10 children, 25 grandchildren
and seven great-grandchildren. They say the secret to a successful
marriage is to concentrate on family, togetherness and working
together to solve problems.
   ``It certainly keeps you together,'' Mrs. Bergthold said. ``The
key is to get mad (with each other) and get over it.''
   Florence and Charlie Lesperance, married on June 24 more than 50
years ago, say their advice for future and present marriages is
having a give-and-take relationship.
   ``You just have to go 50-50,'' Mrs. Lesperance said. ``You win
and he wins. You give in once in a while and he gives in once in a
while.''
   Jill and Bruno Wicker seemed to sum up their feelings for many
couples.
   ``I hope the next 50 are as nice as the first 50,'' Mrs. Wicker
said.
</TEXT>
