<HEAD>Becker Defeats Lendl in 110-Degree Heat for First U.S. Open Win</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wimbledon champion Boris Becker won his first
U.S. Open tennis tournament Sunday by defeating top-ranked Ivan
Lendl in a struggle that lasted nearly four hours as temperatures
climbed to 110 degrees.
   Frequently icing his legs and eating fruit during breaks, the
second seed from West Germany took his fourth Grand Slam title 7-6,
1-6, 6-3, 7-6. He won his third Wimbledon crown in July.
   ``This is much more exhausting,'' Becker said, comparing the Open
to Wimbledon. ``It's even more exhausting than the French Open, with
the heat, the planes and the spectators.''
   The 21-year-old Becker's double success won't be enough to lift
him past Lendl in the computer rankings, but his strong serve and
improved court command were enough to outlast the three-time Open
champion in the three-hour, 51-minute battle.
   Becker's win gave West Germany a sweep of the singles
championships at Wimbledon and the Open. Steffi Graf also won both.
   Becker's Open win earned him $300,000. Lendl, 29, a Czech who now
lives in Greenwich, Conn., earned $150,000.
   In the women's doubles championship finals, Martina Navratilova
and Hana Mandlikova beat Pam Shriver and Mary Jo Fernandez 5-7, 6-4,
6-4. Navratilova and Mandlikova split $104,000. Shriver and
Fernandez divided $52,000.
