<FIRST>r a AM-DrugsPoll     09-10 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs Poll,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Poll: Majority Thinks Drugs Are Biggest Problem Facing Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty-six percent of Americans agree with
President Bush that illegal drugs are the biggest problem facing the
nation, according to an ABC News poll released Sunday.
   Of the 758 people interviewed from Thursday through Saturday, 86
percent said drugs are a bigger problem than the federal budget
deficit, unemployment, AIDS, the crime rate and the threat of
nuclear war.
   Two years ago, the public thought the budget deficit and
unemployment were bigger problems than drugs, the network said.
   The poll found that more than a third of those interviewed have a
friend addicted to illegal drugs, one in five said drugs have caused
problems in their family and the same number said drugs are a
problem at work or school.
   Seventy-three percent said they approved of Bush's call last week
for more money to local law enforcement agencies and 69 percent
supported his plan to use the U.S. military to fight drugs at the
request of foreign countries.
   However, only 37 percent said they supported raising taxes to
wage the war against drugs.
   The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage
points.
   On Saturday, Newsweek released a poll which found that 52 percent
of Americans believe the anti-drug program announced by Bush
proposes spending too little money for such a huge problem.
   The Newsweek poll found that 73 percent would support raising
federal taxes on cigarettes and alcoholic beverages and 65 percent
said they would support a 1 percent surtax on corporate income taxes
to pay for an anti-drug program.
   The Newsweek poll by the Gallup Organization was based on
interviews with 609 adults Thursday and Friday and also had a margin
of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</TEXT>
