<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-Greeting     09-10 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Greeting,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Turn Out to Welcome Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICKELSDORF, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rust-brown car crossed from
Hungary to Austria at midnight as hundreds of Austrians cheered and
whistled their greetings to the first of thousands of East German
refugees to pour into this border town.
   Its male driver, along with another man and two women, grinned
broadly at the Austrian border booth and waved, transfixed in the
glare of TV camera lights, and then moved on.
   Minutes later, 12 men poured out of three Hungarian taxis, some
of them yelling, ``We're free! We're free! It's unbelievable!''
Others popped champagne or yelled greetings to the crowd.
   ``It's wonderful, it's terrific,'' others shouted to Western
reporters amid the honking horns.
   One group of youths, just before crossing the opened red and
white border barriers, held up a sign saying ``Give it up Erich'' _
a reference to the East German communist leader, Erich Honecker.
   The Austrians met the new refugees early Monday with open arms.
The refugees were taking part in the largest mass emigration of East
Germans to West Germany since the Berlin Wall was built in 1961 to
stem the flow across the border.
   Some of the Austrians offered to feed or shelter those wanting to
rest before continuing their journey. One woman stood by the side of
the road with a hand-lettered sign offering room and board for a
refugee family with children.
   Red Cross helpers in Nickelsdorf, 50 miles southeast of Vienna,
busied themselves with handing out steaming cups of tea, crackers,
maps _ and advice _ to the East Germans. Many of the refugees said
they planned to drive directly to the West German border, 400 miles
to the north, where tent communities were awating them.
   At the Nickelsdorf crossing,Austrian customs agents told
reporters they counted 450 cars carrying about 1,200 people in the
first three hours.
   One veteran Red Cross volunteer told reporters the nighttime
influx of refugees from Hungary reminded him of the thousands of
Hungarians who fled over the same border in 1956, after Soviet tanks
crushed the Soviet bloc's bloodiest revolt.
</TEXT>
