<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Jews-Catholics     09-10 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jews-Catholics,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Leader says Papal Attitude should not Halt Ecumenism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish leader on Sunday criticized Pope John Paul
II's attitudes toward Judaism and Israel and urged Jewish people
worldwide to press ecumenical efforts on lower levels of the Roman
Catholic Church.
   Tullia Zevi, president of the Union of Italian Jewish
Communities, said the best progress in Jewish-Catholic relations
could be made with the national bishops' conferences.
   ``They have autonomy to work within their own countries, and in
many nations, they are often one step ahead of the Vatican,'' she
told a meeting of the European Jewish Congress.
   The congress met in London as a dispute brews between the
international Jewish community and the Roman Catholic Church over a
convent built at the Auschwitz concentration camp in Poland. At
least 2.5 million Jews died there during World War II.
   A 1987 accord between Jewish and Catholic representatives
stipulated the convent should be moved by Feb. 22, but the deadline
passed and the convent remained. The Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef
Glemp, has termed the accord ``offensive.''
   The Polish-born pope has not taken a firm public stand on the
dispute.
   Before becoming pope in 1979, John Paul was the archbishop of
Krakow, in the archdiocese where Auschwitz lies.
   Mrs. Zevi, a signatory of the convent accord, said that in recent
apostolic letters about World War II the pope spoke harshly of the
Nazi genocide of Jews and affirmed that hatred of Judaism conflicted
with Christian tenets.
   But acknowledgement of horrors of the past and warnings about the
way the Gospel is taught ``are not reflected in the pope's theology
and politics as far as Jews and Judaism are concerned,'' she said.
   The apostolic letters and the Auschwitz convent controversy ``are
symptomatic of a pattern aimed to revise the history of the
Holocaust and the role of the church during that terrible period,''
Mrs. Zevi said.
   ``He is seeking to `Christianize' the Holocaust by means of
churches and convents in the extermination camps, he has proclaimed
the sainthood of Edith Stein, a Jewish nun, and continues to keep
the state of Israel in a diplomatic limbo,'' Mrs. Zevi said.
   But she said the Catholic-Jewish dialogue that has grown since
the 1962-65 Second Vatican Council, ``is more important than any
individual pope, and we must ensure that it continues.''
   In 1965, the Vatican Council issued the document ``Nostra
Aetate'' (``In Our Times''), which officially rescinded the
accusation that the Jews killed Christ. It is considered a turning
point in Catholic-Jewish relations.
</TEXT>
