<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     09-10 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend First Opposition Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUIGALPA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people waving
blue-and-white Nicaraguan flags marched through the streets of this
cattle town Sunday in the first campaign rally by the opposition for
the February elections.
   Violeta Barrios de Chamorro, presidential candidate of the
National Opposition Union, in a 10-minute speech spoke of her four
children, divided along pro- and anti-Sandinista lines, and urged
the people to pray for peace.
   Her running mate, vice presidential candidate Virgilio Godoy of
the Liberal Independent Party, drew cheers as he criticized the
amount of money the governing Sandinistas spend on the armed forces
and the presence of Soviet-bloc advisers in Nicaragua.
   ``What do the people want?'' Godoy asked.
   ``For the (Sandinista) Front to leave!'' the crowd shouted back.
   ``And for Cuba to leave, and for the Soviets to leave, and for
(North) Korea to leave,'' Godoy responded to rounds of applause.
   An estimated 6,000 people attended the rally of the 14-party
opposition coalition.
   Four U.N. observers and one representative from the Organization
of American States also were at the rally in this town 85 miles east
of Managua, the capital.
   Mrs. Chamorro, a director of the opposition newspaper La Prensa,
drew cheers when she spoke of her husband, La Prensa publisher Pedro
Joaquin Chamorro, who was assassinated in Managua in 1978. His
murder led to the revolt, spearheaded by the Sandinistas, that
ousted the conservative regime of President Anastasio Somoza in July
1979.
   Mrs. Chamorro said ``the first inheritance'' from her husband was
``to be a Chamorro, even though they may want to take it away from
me.'' She referred to reports the government-controlled news media
have been told to use only her maident name of Barrios.
   A native of the town of Rivas in southwestern Nicaragua, the
59-year-old presidential nominee reminisced about her childhood when
her parents went to buy cattle in Juigalpa, the main town in
Chontales province.
   Rep. Bill Grant, D-Fla., one of four congressmen visiting
Managua, told a news conference if the Feb. 25 balloting is free and
fair ``there will be an improvement in U.S.-Nicaraguan relations no
matter who wins.''
   But ``if the Nicaraguan government, for whatever excuse, decides
to postpone or cancel the elections, I'm confident that the U.S.
Congress will increase its support to the Contras in the future,''
he added. Nicaraguan rebels fighting the Sandinistas are known as
Contras.
   Grant also said that at a meeting Sunday, President Daniel Ortega
promised to ``revise'' the case of two U.S. fishing boats and their
crews seized last month on charges of fishing illegaly in Nicaraguan
waters. Grant did not give any details.
   The fishing vessels Pete's Dream and Pescardora and their eight
crewmen have been held in the Carribbean port of Bluefields since
Aug. 28.
   Grant and Republican Reps. Doug Bereuter of Nebraska, Mickey
Edwards of Oklahoma and Elton Gallegly of California arrived in
Nicaragua Saturday as part of a tour of Central America and left for
Washington Sunday.
</TEXT>
