<FIRST>u a AM-ChopperCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0742 09-10 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chopper Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0742,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Helicopters Crash in Idaho, Pacific; Three Dead, Three Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-9, `The Navy ...,' with 8 grafs to CORRECT that
helicopter launched from ship, sted traveling from San Diego, UPDATE with
details on crash, search for missing, CORRECT name of peak in Idaho crash
to `Danskin,' sted `Danksin;' picks up 10th graf, `Sgt. Gary ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy helicopter crashed off the California coast Sunday,
leaving three people missing, and the wreckage of a National Guard
chopper that went down in Idaho, killing three, was found in a
remote mountain area.
   Three of the six people aboard the Navy UH-1N ``Huey'' were
pulled from the Pacific Ocean, and one man survived the crash of the
Idaho Army National Guard UH-1H ``Huey,'' which had been missing
since Saturday evening, officials said.
   It was not known what caused either crash.
   The Navy helicopter that plunged into the sea around 11:30 a.m.
PDT had taken off from the amphibious assault ship USS Peleliu and
was circling in case other aircraft taking part in a military
exercise experienced problems, said Marine Capt. Chris Gillette.
   A lookout aboard the Peleliu saw the Huey go down about three
miles from the ship, and sounded the alarm, Gillette said from Camp
Pendleton, Calif., a Marine base 18 miles northeast of the crash
site.
   The ship dispatched a motorboat, which picked up three crewmen,
and helicopters to search for the missing crew members.
   The three who were rescued were taken to Balboa Navy Hospital in
San Diego, Gillette said. One victim was in serious but stable
condition with a head injury; the other two received minor injuries.
   Gillette said the search for the missing would continue through
the night.
   None of the people aboard the helicopter was identified, but all
were Navy personnel, the Marines said.
   The Peleliu, based in Long Beach, Calif., was one of six Navy
ships taking part in ``Kernel Usher 89-3,'' a nine-day exercise
involving more than 15,000 Navy and Marine personnel, said Marine
1st Lt. Patrick Givens.
   In Idaho, Guard search helicopters found the helicopter's
wreckage 25 miles southeast of Boise near Danskin Peak at 9:02 a.m.
MDT, said Maj. Jim Ball. A rescue unit was dispatched.
   Sgt. Gary L. Scheer, 29, of Boise, who suffered broken bones and
internal injuries, was in serious condition at St. Alphonsus
Regional Medical Center, Ball said.
   Killed were the pilots _ Chief Warrant Officer 4 James R. Bollar,
39, of McCall and Chief Warrant Officer 4 Dickie C. Hill, 46, of
Boise _ and Sgt. Charles L. Hansen, 28, of Boise, the crew chief.
   The Huey, a Vietnam-era aircraft about 20 years old, left Gowen
Field in Boise around 5 p.m. Saturday on a training mission, and had
been due to return by 6:30 p.m.
   When the aircraft did not turn up, Guard helicopters were
dispatched to search a 200-square-mile area west of the South Fork
of the Boise River.
   Search efforts were called off at midnight Saturday and resumed
at sunrise Sunday.
   The accident will investigated by the U.S. Army Aviation Safety
Center at Fort Rucker, Ala., Ball said.
</TEXT>
