<SECOND>AM-Obit-Dunfey, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0754,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walter Dunfey, Co-Founder of Dunfey Hotels, Dead at 57</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with three grafs to CORRECT that Dunfey was former director
of hotels. Picks up 4th graf, `Dunfey was...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter Dunfey, co-founder and former director of
Dunfey Hotels and a leader in New Hampshire's Democratic Party, died
Sunday at Massachusetts General Hospital. He was 57.
   Dunfey, of Rye, N.H., died from complications related to an
aneurysm he suffered Aug. 3, the company said in statement.
   Dunfey helped build his Dunfey Hotels business into an
international corporation, which was later sold and is now known as
Omni Hotels. In December 1987, he and four of his brothers formed
the Dunfey Brothers Capital Group, a venture capital and investment
company.
   Dunfey also was involved heavily in democratic politics, both at
the state and national levels. He was a member of the Democratic
National Committee's Business Council, as well as its Convention
Site Selection Committee.
   Dunfey also served on the Democratic National Committee's Hunt
Commission, which examined the presidential primary system, and was
instrumental in preserving New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation
primary status.
   In 1960, then Sen. John Kennedy began his presidential campaign
from Dunfey's office in the Carpenter Hotel in Manchester, N.H.
   ``He never asked for anything from anybody, but he was first one
that people _ candidates, politicians _ asked for help,'' said Paul
McEachern, a former gubernatorial candidate in New Hampshire and
close friend of Dunfey.
   Dunfey also was involved with many charities. He was founder of
the American-Ireland Fund's New Hampshire chapter, and also served
as national director and treasurer for the organization that
promotes Irish culture and a peaceful end to the violence in
Northern Ireland.
   Dunfey is survived by his wife, Barbara Reynolds Dunfey, a
daughter, two sons, six brothers, three sisters and six
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
