<FIRST>r f BC-Holylake-FarmersGroup     09-10 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Holylake-Farmers Group,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Goldsmith's Bid to Block State Review of BAT Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has denied Sir James
Goldsmith's attempt to block Washington state insurance regulators
from reviewing his bid to buy B.A.T. Industries PLC, the parent of
Farmer's Group Inc., citing constitutional protections.
   Judge Robert Bryan on Friday rejected Goldsmith's request for a
preliminary injunction, thereby refusing to strike down Washington's
right to approve or deny the transaction.
   Washington is one of nine states in which Goldsmith has filed
federal lawsuits attempting to prevent state regulatory reviews of
the proposed hostile takeover.
   Farmers, a Los Angeles-based insurance company, has insurance
operations in all nine states. Goldsmith wants to buy its British
parent for about $22 billion through his Hoylake Investments Ltd.
   With Friday's ruling, federal judges in Texas and Washington have
rejected Goldsmith's attempt to avoid state review. Hearings in the
other seven states are pending.
   In a news release, Hoylake said the decision would be appealed.
   ``Subjecting a wholly foreign securities transaction to state
regulatory review clearly exceeds the constitutional limitation on
state authority,'' the company said.
   Ed Southon, Washington deputy insurance commissioner, said his
office was pleased with the judge's decision. A hearing on Hoylake's
bid is scheduled for Oct. 10, and Southon said he expects a ruling
from the state insurance commissioner to be issued before Oct. 28.
</TEXT>
