<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1615EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-China-GATT     09-10 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-GATT,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expected To Resume Talks Aimed At Membership, GAAT Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUERGENSTOCK, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is expected to resume
efforts soon to join the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade,
GATT's director-general said.
   Arthur Dunkel of Switzerland said that officials from China,
whose application for GATT membership was temporarily shelved after
the bloody crackdown on student-led protests in June, plan to hold
discussions with GATT members about reviving talks on membership.
   ``Some days from now, there will be extensive informal
consultations in Geneva with Chinese authorities to see where things
stand,'' Dunkel said in an interview Saturday with The Associated
Press. He declined to elaborate.
   A 46-member GATT group set up to examine Beijing's bid put off
further meetings indefinitely after the crackdown because many
delegates felt the political turmoil precluded progress on practical
issues.
   China applied in 1986 to join GATT, a 96-nation market-oriented
group whose members pledge to bring their policies in line with its
free-trade rules. GATT has its headquarters in Geneva.
   Dunkel said he also expected the Soviet Union to apply for
membership at some point as part of its effort to move toward a more
market-oriented economy.
   ``But this isn't something for tomorrow,'' he said.
   He added, however, that since the current round of GATT world
trade talks began in 1986, Soviet trade authorities have been kept
informed of the progress of the negotiations.
   Every change in Soviet trade legislation since then ``has been
made in such a way that it will facilitate the entry of the U.S.S.R.
into GATT,'' Dunkel said.
   Dunkel was interviewed while attending a conference of the Swiss
Commodities, Futures and Options Association.
</TEXT>
