<FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OutsideMagazine Bjt   09-10 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Outside Magazine, Bjt,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher: Capture Armchair Adventurers But Keep Loyalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of mellow marketing, Outside magazine
is about to undertake an ambitious public relations assault to try
to raise its profile and nearly double its circulation.
   But the publisher of the 13-year-old adventure magazine says he
needs to walk the fine line between attracting the armchair
adventure crowd and not losing its base of rock-climbers in cutoffs.
   ``We want to make editorial changes that drive the product
upscale,'' said Larry Burke, whose brash entrepreneurship pushed the
magazine through various formats since 1976.
   ``In the '60s and '70s, the Baby Boomers were going out with 60
pounds of gear on their backs in a pack, and now those same people
are more likely to want to go hiking _ yes, maybe with a baby in the
backpack _ from hut to hut in the Sierras or in Europe.''
   The magazine, a winner in 1984 for general excellence and again
in 1987 for essays and criticism in the National Magazine Awards,
takes its readers on first-person adventures and exploits that would
knock the fedora off cinematic pretender Indiana Jones.
   It also is known for its inspired writing and offbeat subject
matter.
   Woody Allen, the English poet John Donne and algebraic
formulation were once called upon by writer David Quammen to cast
light upon the forces that incite Chinook salmon to struggle
mightily and then die in the noble act of procreation.
   Quammen has also written about homosexual behavior among bedbugs
and the proper method for preparing and serving the Guam fruit bat
as supper _ including swallowing the fur. It was Quammen who brought
the 1987 award.
   Freelance writer Donald R. Katz, another contributor, has written
about coon-dog racing, NASA's research on vomiting in space and the
sport of ferret-legging, which involves the ``tying of a
competitor's trousers at the ankles and the subsequent insertion
into those trousers of a couple of peculiarly vicious fur-coated
foot-long carnivores called ferrets.''
   ``Outside pays you in sensitivity to your writing, in freedom of
subject matter and in gorgeous presentation,'' said Katz, noting the
relatively low monetary payment for articles. ``It is considered a
place where you can have fun writing.''
   Burke, 47, pulled the magazine's pieces together gradually. In
1976, he hired a small staff and hid expenses from his family
business, an advertising display company, to finance the magazine,
then called ``Mariah'' after the wind. But at the same time, another
adventure magazine was being bankrolled by $2 million in profits
from Rolling Stone magazine.
   That magazine, called ``Outside,'' began to falter with an
overbudgeted staff and undersold advertising, and the two combined
in 1978 under Burke, who now controls the magazine.
   Circulation stands at 300,000, compared to about 90,000 for
``Mariah,'' with annual profits nearing $2.3 million.
   The magazine is familiar to most hard-core outdoors enthusiasts,
but Burke wants to make ``Outside'' a household word among the less
adventurous, too.
   He recently hired additional advertising staff and a public
relations firm to target slightly older, more affluent readers.
   Burke's also developing his idea for a Camp Outside, an adventure
vacation camp for children and adults.
   Like a true adventurist, Burke relishes the heights of the
challenge before him.
   ``We are undermarketed,'' he said, ``and while that might depress
some people, I look at it as a great opportunity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
