<FIRST>u f AM-LatinAmerica 1stLd-Writethru f0011 09-10 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Latin America, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0011,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latin Incomes Fell, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to ADD Brazil; Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Individual incomes in Latin America dropped
overall last year and will drop further, the Inter-American
Development Bank said Sunday in a report that shows regional growth
at less than 1 percent in 1988.
   According to the bank, 1988 per capita income was lower in 12 of
25 Latin American countries, including three of the most populous
and heavily indebted: Mexico, Brazil and Argentina.
   The bank did not provide dollar figures in its report, but World
Bank statistics for 1987 show that the average Argentine earned the
equivalent of $2,370, the average Brazilian $2,020 and the average
Mexican $1,820.
   The comparable U.S. income was $18,430 in 1987, the most recent
year for which the World Bank figures are available.
   The Inter-American bank said the 1988 drop was the greatest in
Panama _ 18.8 percent _ followed by Nicaragua and Peru with 11.1
percent each.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions against both
Panama and Nicaragua. Peru's problems worsened last year after a
surge in growth during 1986 and 1987.
   In one country, Bolivia, the average income appeared static in
1988.
   The other 12 countries showed increases, with the best record in
Chile. The World Bank put income there at $1,310 in 1987. The IADB
reported an increase of 5.6 percent last year.
   ``Once more it was a very bad year for Latin America,'' bank
President Enrique V. Iglesias said. ``The overall growth was a very
disappointing figure.''
   Iglesias plans to release the report formally at a news
conference Thursday.
   The report said the area's total income grew by 0.6 percent.
Since the population grows much faster _ over 2 percent a year _
that translated into an average decline of 1.5 percent for
individuals.
   Iglesias said this year's total income figure would be worse,
only a little over zero overall. That could mean a 2 percent drop
for the average Latin American.
   He called the increase of inflation the top negative development
of 1988. The International Monetary Fund has reported that prices in
Brazil, which accounts for one-third of the area's production, rose
at an annual rate of 854 percent in April compared with a year
earlier.
   ``The overall upsurge of inflation in 1988 reached 100 percent,
weighted by population,'' Iglesias said.
   He added that the rise in prices affects the political as well as
the economic situation.
   His bank, owned by 44 governments, is a major source of loans to
raise living standards in countries of Latin America and the
Caribbean. It authorized $1.16 billion in new lending last year. The
United States is the largest shareholder.
   Willy Van Ryckeghem, head of the bank's country studies division,
said there was encouraging news from the region. He said exports
from Latin America last year grew twice as fast as world trade as a
whole.
   He also pointed out that for the first time in recent years there
was a reduction in the area's foreign debt. He attributed that drop
largely to ``debt-equity swaps.'' In such deals, Latin American
debtors who owe debts to foreigners _ usually foreign banks _ in
dollars or other hard currencies are allowed to pay in their own
currency. The creditor then uses the money to buy property or
business in that country.
   The report estimated foreign debt of the 25 countries at $426
billion in 1988, down from $441 billion the year before.
</TEXT>
