<FIRST>r f AM-Generic-Sentencing     09-10 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic-Sentencing,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dingell, Bliley Say Cooperation Has Been Grudging and Limited</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Generic Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of a House subcommittee told a federal
judge who will sentence former officials of two generic drug
manufacturers that the companies have not cooperated fully with the
panel and have misled investigators.
   In a letter to U.S. District Judge John R. Hargrove in Baltimore,
U.S. Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce investigations subcommittee, and Thomas Bliley, R-Va., the
panel's ranking Republican, said the companies' cooperation has been
``grudging and limited.''
   The letter was released Sunday by the congressmen.
   Ashok Patel, former senior vice president of Par Pharmaceuticals
Inc. of Spring Valley, N.Y., and Dilip Shah, former president of
Quad Pharmaceutical Inc., an Indianapolis-based subsidiary of Par,
pleaded guilty to bribing Food and Drug Administration chemists to
win approval for generic drug applications.
   The congressmen, whose panel initiated an inquiry into the
generic drug industry that has resulted in charges against three FDA
employees and action to take dozens of generic drugs off the market,
told the judge the problems within the two companies are
``widespread.''
   ``Wholesale management changes will be needed to eradicate the
corporate cultures that helped lead to the charges before you,''
Dingell and Bliley told the judge.
   Current and former officials of the two companies, including
Ashok and Patel, were subpoenaed to testify before the subcommittee
Monday.
   FDA officials also were scheduled to testify about recent
inspections at the plants of 11 generic drug companies being
investigated by the agency.
</TEXT>
