<FIRST>r f BC-Mazda-Semiconductors     09-10 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mazda-Semiconductors,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazada Says It Will Increase Use Of Foreign Semiconductors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mazda Motor Corp., the Japanese carmaker, said
Sunday it would increase its use of non-Japanese semiconductors
sevenfold to $8.9 million a year by 1992 compared with the 1988
level.
   The company said it planned to use $2.7 million worth of foreign
semiconductors in its cars this year.
   To achieve its goal, Mazda said it plans to establish a Foreign
Semiconductor Procurement Promotion Committee incorporating the
company's electronic component suppliers through whom the parts will
be purchased.
   Under a policy of expanding the use of foreign control parts in
its cars, Mazda said it uses foreign electronic control units in the
air bag system of its MX-5 Miata two-seat sports car and in the
air-bag control system of its MPV minivan, B-Series pickup truck and
four-wheel-drive 323 models.
   Nearly 100 percent of the semiconductors in these systems are
foreign-made, coming from such U.S. companies as Motorola Inc.,
Intel Corp. and National Semiconductor Corp., Mazda said in a press
release issued from Detroit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
